<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S2.SS2">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.2 </span>Markovian Dynamical S=
ystems</h3><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report=
 issue for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.7">In the most general case, an indivisi=
ble dynamical system will not
provide a way to evolve a system from a <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_ital=
ic" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.7.1">non-initial</em> target
time <math alttext=3D"t^{\prime}\neq 0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inlin=
e" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>t</=
mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><mo>=E2=89=A0</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation =
encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t^{\prime}\neq 0</annotation></semantics></m=
ath> to another target time <math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>t</mi>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t</annotation></semantics></math=
>. An indivisible
dynamical system will also generically lack any means of =E2=80=98dividing
up=E2=80=99 the evolution from <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" displ=
ay=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.3.m3" intent=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math> t=
o <math alttext=3D"t\neq 0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.=
SS2.p1.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>=E2=89=A0</=
mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t\neq 0</ann=
otation></semantics></math> into well-defined
forms of evolution over intermediate time durations between <math alttext=
=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.5.m5" intent=
=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math> and
<math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.6=
.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>t</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">t</annotation></semantics></math> (even assuming that the set=
 of times <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inlin=
e" id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.7.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_fo=
nt_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-=
tex">\mathcal{T}</annotation></semantics></math> has a notion
of ordering). To make contact with the kinds of dynamical systems
considered more widely in the research literature, it will therefore
be necessary to introduce a somewhat less general class of mathematical
structures.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Re=
port issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S2.SS2.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S2.SS2.p2.1">This paper will define a Markovian (o=
r divisible) dynamical system
to be a tuple of the form</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"disp=
lay: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
