<li class=3D"ltx_item" id=3D"S3.I1.i15" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.6">These notions of indivisibility an=
d non-Markovianity represent a distinct
way to generalize the Markovian case, as compared with most forms
of non-Markovianity described in textbooks and in the research literature.
According to those more traditional forms of non-Markovianity, as
emphasized by Gillespie (1998, 2000),
one assumes that the set of target times <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}" clas=
s=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.1.m1" intent=3D":liter=
al"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{T}</annotation></semantics>=
</math> has an ordering
relation, and one further assumes the existence of higher-order conditional
probabilities <math alttext=3D"p\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1=
};j_{2},t_{2};\dots}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline=
" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><=
mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo fence=3D"fa=
lse" rspace=3D"0.167em" stretchy=3D"false">|</mo><msub><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn>=
</msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>;</mo><msub><mi>j</mi=
><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>;</mo><mi =
mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annota=
tion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1}=
,t_{1};j_{2},t_{2};\dots}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
that are conditioned on arbitrarily many conditioning times <math alttext=
=3D"t_{1},t_{2},\dots" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.I1.i1=
5.p1.3.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn><=
/msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=
=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex"=
>t_{1},t_{2},\dots</annotation></semantics></math>.
From that more traditional standpoint, the system is Markovian if
and only if the latest conditioning time <math alttext=3D"t_{1}" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><s=
emantics><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><annotation encoding=3D"applicati=
on/x-tex">t_{1}</annotation></semantics></math> always screens off
all the earlier conditioning times <math alttext=3D"t_{2},\dots" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.5.m5" intent=3D":literal"><s=
emantics><mrow><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=
=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex"=
>t_{2},\dots</annotation></semantics></math>, so that <math alttext=3D"p\ma=
thopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1};j_{2},t_{2};\dots}}\right)=3Dp\ma=
thopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unpar=
sed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.I1.i15.p1.6.m6" intent=3D":literal"><seman=
tics><mrow><mrow><mi>p</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</=
mo><mi>t</mi><mo fence=3D"false" rspace=3D"0.167em" stretchy=3D"false">|</m=
o><msub><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></ms=
ub><mo>;</mo><msub><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn=
>2</mn></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi></mrow></m=
row><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=3D</mo><mi>p</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><=
mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo fence=3D"false" rspace=3D"0.167em" stretch=
y=3D"false">|</mo><msub><mi>j</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>t</m=
i><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-tex">p\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1};j_{2},t_{2}=
;\dots}}\right)=3Dp\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i,t|j_{1},t_{1}}}\right)</a=
nnotation></semantics></math>.
The definition of an indivisible stochastic process presented in this
paper does not assume fixed values of such higher-order conditional
probabilities in the first place, and therefore, in a sense, represents
a whole equivalence class of non-Markovian models, each of which is
called a non-Markovian realizer. In particular, an indivisible stochastic
process is defined by fixing less information than any of its non-Markovian
realizers.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Rep=
ort issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
</li>
