<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.6">In a sense, the absolutely <em class=
=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.6.1">most</em> <em class=3D"l=
tx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.6.2">general</em> kind of stochast=
ic
mathematical structure is simply called a stochastic process, and
essentially requires only the specification of a state space <math alttext=
=3D"\mathcal{X}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.1.m1=
" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=
=9D=92=B3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{X}</annot=
ation></semantics></math>,
a set of target times <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}" class=3D"ltx_Math" disp=
lay=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi cla=
ss=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-tex">\mathcal{T}</annotation></semantics></math>, an initial pr=
obability distribution
<math alttext=3D"p" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.3=
.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>p</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math>, and a set of one or more t=
ime-dependent random variables <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{A}" class=3D"ltx_M=
ath" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantic=
s><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi><annotation encod=
ing=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{A}</annotation></semantics></math>.<span=
 class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote6"><sup class=3D"ltx_no=
te_mark">6</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_cont=
ent"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">6</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_not=
e">6</span>See Rosenblatt (1962), Parzen (1962), Doob (1990), or Ross (1995=
)
for textbook treatments.</span></span></span> Importantly, the definition o=
f a stochastic process lacks the specification
of a dynamical law. By requiring a dynamical law in the form of a
transition map <math alttext=3D"\Gamma" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inlin=
e" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.5.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi mathvariant=3D"=
normal">=CE=93</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma</annot=
ation></semantics></math>, an indivisible stochastic process
<math alttext=3D"\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{T},\math=
cal{T}_{0},\Gamma,p,\mathcal{A}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" displ=
ay=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p3.6.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><m=
row><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=
=92=9E</mi><mo>,</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</m=
i><mo>,</mo><msub><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><=
mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mo>,</mo><=
mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi>=
</mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\=
mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{T},\mathcal{T}_{0},\Gamma,=
p,\mathcal{A}}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
is not quite as general as a stochastic process, but will still be
general enough to encompass a large class of physical and mathematical
models.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report=
 issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.11">In particular, one can regard any Ma=
rkov chain as a special case of
an indivisible stochastic process. The starting place is to assume
that the set of target times <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}" class=3D"ltx_Mat=
h" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics>=
<mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><annotation encodin=
g=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{T}</annotation></semantics></math> and the=
 set of conditioning
times <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}_{0}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inlin=
e" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi class=3D"=
ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{T}_{0}</annotation></semantics></math>=
 are identical and are both isomorphic to
the integers, <math alttext=3D"\mathcal{T}=3D\mathcal{T}_{0}\cong\mathbb{Z}=
" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.3.m3" intent=3D":li=
teral"><semantics><mrow><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF=
</mi><mo>=3D</mo><msub><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF<=
/mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=E2=89=85</mo><mi>=E2=84=A4</mi></mrow><annotation=
 encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathcal{T}=3D\mathcal{T}_{0}\cong\mathbb{Z=
}</annotation></semantics></math>, with
each time <math alttext=3D"t=3Dn\,\delta t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"i=
nline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi=
><mo>=3D</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.170em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=
=8B</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>=
t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t=3Dn\,\delt=
a t</annotation></semantics></math> an integer number <math alttext=3D"n\in=
\mathbb{Z}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.5.m5" int=
ent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mi>=E2=84=A4=
</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">n\in\mathbb{Z}</anno=
tation></semantics></math> of
steps of some fixed, elementary time scale <math alttext=3D"\delta t" class=
=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.6.m6" intent=3D":literal">=
<semantics><mrow><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B=
</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\delta t</=
annotation></semantics></math>. One then further
assumes that for each integer <math alttext=3D"n" class=3D"ltx_Math" displa=
y=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.7.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>n</mi=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">n</annotation></semantics></mat=
h>, the time-dependent transition
matrix <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(n\,\delta t\left=
arrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.S=
S3.p4.8.m8" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal"=
>=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mi>t</=
mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo><=
/mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclos=
e{{\left(n\,\delta t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math> o=
riginally
defined in (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.03085v=
2#S3.E44" title=3D"In 2nd item =E2=80=A3 3.2 Ingredients from Linear Algebr=
a =E2=80=A3 3 Stochastic Processes =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Theorem=
"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">44</span></a>) can be expressed as t=
he
<math alttext=3D"n" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.9=
.m9" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>n</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">n</annotation></semantics></math>th power of the transition m=
atrix <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\delta t}}\right)=
\equiv\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\delta t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.10.m10" intent=
=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi>=
<mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)=
</mo></mrow><mo>=E2=89=A1</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><=
mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=
=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D=
"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\delta t}}\right)\eq=
uiv\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\delta t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annota=
tion></semantics></math>
that implements the evolution for just the first time step <math alttext=3D=
"\delta t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S3.SS3.p4.11.m11" in=
tent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=
=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application=
/x-tex">\delta t</annotation></semantics></math>:</p><button class=3D"sr-on=
ly button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</but=
ton>
