span></td>
</tr></tbody>
</table>
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS1.p2.1">Remarkably, to study the class of ind=
ivisible stochastic process,
this theorem implies that it suffices to restrict one=E2=80=99s attention
to the subclass of unistochastic processes.</p><button class=3D"sr-only but=
ton" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S4.SS2">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.2 </span>Corollaries of the Th=
eorem</h3><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report =
issue for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS2.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS2.p1.1">The proof of the stochastic-quantum t=
heorem (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.03085v2#S4=
.E69" title=3D"In 4.1 Statement of the Theorem =E2=80=A3 4 The Stochastic-Q=
uantum Theorem =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Theorem"><span class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_ref_tag">69</span></a>)
will involve the construction of a representation of the given indivisible
stochastic process in the formalism of Hilbert spaces, and will show
that every indivisible stochastic process corresponds to a unitarily
evolving quantum system in a Hilbert space. One thereby turns some
of the puzzling axiomatic ingredients of quantum theory=E2=80=94the
complex numbers,<span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote11=
"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">11</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span=
 class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">11</sup><span clas=
s=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">11</span>Time-reversal transformations for quant=
um systems are carried out
by anti-unitary operators, which take the general form <math alttext=3D"VK"=
 class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.m1" intent=3D":lite=
ral"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B=
</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">VK</annota=
tion></semantics></math>, where
<math alttext=3D"V" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.=
m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>V</mi><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">V</annotation></semantics></math> is unitary and <math alttext=
=3D"K" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.m3" intent=3D=
":literal"><semantics><mi>K</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">=
K</annotation></semantics></math> is an abstract operator that carries out
complex-conjugation. By definition, <math alttext=3D"K^{2}=3D1" class=3D"lt=
x_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semant=
ics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=3D</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">K^{2}=3D1</annotation></semantics><=
/math> and <math alttext=3D"Ki=3D-iK" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline"=
 id=3D"footnote11.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>K</mi>=
<mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>i</mi></mrow><mo>=3D</m=
o><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em"=
>=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">Ki=3D-iK</annotation></semantics></math>, where
<math alttext=3D"i\equiv\sqrt{-1}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote11.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=E2=
=89=A1</mo><msqrt><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msqrt></mrow><=
annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">i\equiv\sqrt{-1}</annotation></se=
mantics></math> is the imaginary unit. One can therefore show
that <math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footno=
te11.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-tex">i</annotation></semantics></math>, <math alttext=3D"K" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.m8" intent=3D":literal=
"><semantics><mi>K</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">K</annota=
tion></semantics></math>, and <math alttext=3D"iK" class=3D"ltx_Math" displ=
ay=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote11.m9" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi=
>i</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">iK</annotation></semantics></math> =
generate a Clifford algebra called the
pseudo-quaternions (Stueckelberg 1960).
As a consequence, there is a sense in which quantum systems are actually
defined over the pseudo-quaternions, rather than merely over the complex
numbers, although only the complex numbers are typically used in the
construction of observables.</span></span></span> Hilbert spaces, linear-un=
itary time evolution, and the Born rule
in particular=E2=80=94into the output of a theorem.</p><button class=3D"sr-=
only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</b=
utton>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS2.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS2.p2.1">It follows from the stochastic-quantu=
m theorem that all indivisible
stochastic processes (at least those based on finite configuration
spaces) can be modeled in terms of unitarily evolving quantum systems.
From this perspective, unitarily evolving quantum systems actually
represent the most general way to model a system with stochastic dynamical
laws.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report i=
ssue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS2.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS2.p3.1">As shown in other work (Barandes 2025=
),
one can go in the other logical direction and show that any comprehensive
quantum system that includes measuring devices and observers as part
of the system can be modeled as an indivisible stochastic process.
Altogether, one thereby arrives at an important new correspondence
between indivisible stochastic processes and quantum systems, called
the stochastic-quantum correspondence, that provides a new way to
think about the physical meaning of quantum theory.</p><button class=3D"sr-=
only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</b=
utton>
</div>
</section>
