<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.10">Markovian-homogeneous dynamical syst=
ems of this kind provide a discretization
of many of the kinds of deterministic, logically time-reversible systems
that show up in classical physics.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" styl=
e=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.14">Letting <math alttext=3D"\delta t" c=
lass=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.1.m1" intent=3D":liter=
al"><semantics><mrow><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=
=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\del=
ta t</annotation></semantics></math> be the elementary duration of a single=
 time step,
and letting <math alttext=3D"n\in\mathbb{Z}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"=
inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</m=
i><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mi>=E2=84=A4</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">n\in\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math> denote an integ=
er number of time steps,
the system=E2=80=99s specific state <math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx_Math" =
display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.3.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi=
>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">i</annotation></semantics=
></math> at the time <math alttext=3D"t=3Dn\,\delta t" class=3D"ltx_Math" d=
isplay=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mro=
w><mi>t</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.170em" rspace=3D"0e=
m">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B=
</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">t=
=3Dn\,\delta t</annotation></semantics></math> can
be identified with an <math alttext=3D"N\times 1" class=3D"ltx_Math" displa=
y=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.5.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi=
>N</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mn>1</mn></mro=
w><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times 1</annotation></semant=
ics></math> column vector with a <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" dis=
play=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.6.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mn>1<=
/mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></=
math> in its
<math alttext=3D"i" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.7=
.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">i</annotation></semantics></math>th entry and <math alttext=
=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.8.m8" intent=
=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math>s in all its other entries. Moreover, the ti=
me-dependent
dynamical map <math alttext=3D"f_{n\,\delta t}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.9.m9" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>=
f</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.170em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><=
mi>=CE=B4</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></m=
row></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">f_{n\,\delta t}</anno=
tation></semantics></math> can be expressed as the <math alttext=3D"n" clas=
s=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.10.m10" intent=3D":litera=
l"><semantics><mi>n</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">n</annot=
ation></semantics></math>th power
of a fixed permutation matrix <math alttext=3D"\Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math" d=
isplay=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.11.m11" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><m=
i mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-t=
ex">\Sigma</annotation></semantics></math>, meaning a matrix
consisting of only <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline=
" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.12.m12" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></math>s and <=
math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.13=
.m13" intent=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math>s, with a single <math alttext=
=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p2.14.m14" intent=
=3D":literal"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-te=
x">1</annotation></semantics></math> in each row
and in each column.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: n=
one;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS3.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS3.p3.4">Every permutation matrix is unitary, =
and is also unistochastic, because
computing the modulus-squares of <math alttext=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" dis=
play=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p3.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mn>1<=
/mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">1</annotation></semantics></=
math>s and <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"=
S4.SS3.p3.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math>s gives back <math alt=
text=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p3.3.m3" inte=
nt=3D":literal"><semantics><mn>1</mn><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-=
tex">1</annotation></semantics></math>s
and <math alttext=3D"0" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.=
p3.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><mn>0</mn></math>s. Hence, a discrete Markovia=
n-homogeneous dynamical system
defined in this way is already a unistochastic process, and therefore
trivially satisfies the stochastic-quantum theorem (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" hr=
ef=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.03085v2#S4.E69" title=3D"In 4.1 Statement=
 of the Theorem =E2=80=A3 4 The Stochastic-Quantum Theorem =E2=80=A3 The St=
ochastic-Quantum Theorem"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">69</span></a=
>).</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report iss=
ue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.8">Interestingly, there exists an analyt=
ic interpolation of this <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S4.SS=
3.p4.8.1">discrete-time</em>
unistochastic process that yields a corresponding <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx=
_font_italic" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.8.2">continuous-time</em>
unistochastic process, at the cost of introducing nontrivial stochasticity
into the intervals between the discrete time steps. This new unistochastic
process is based on a time-dependent unistochastic matrix <math alttext=3D"=
\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_mat=
h_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><s=
emantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><=
mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></=
mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mat=
hopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></m=
ath>
whose entries are the modulus-squares of the corresponding entries
of the <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"S4.SS3.p4.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo lspa=
ce=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semantics></math> uni=
tary time-evolution operator defined by <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathc=
lose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)\equiv\Sigma^{t/\delta t}" class=3D"ltx_m=
ath_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.3.m3" intent=3D":literal">=
<semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo str=
etchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo><mo>=E2=89=
=A1</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><msup><mi></mi><mrow><mrow><m=
i>t</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=
=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)\equiv\Sig=
ma^{t/\delta t}</annotation></semantics></math>,
and therefore satisfies <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left=
(n\,\delta t\leftarrow 0}}\right)=3D\Sigma^{n}" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed"=
 display=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><m=
row><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><m=
i>n</mi><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0=
</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo><mo>=3D</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3<=
/mi><msup><mi></mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applicat=
ion/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(n\,\delta t\leftarrow 0}}\rig=
ht)=3D\Sigma^{n}</annotation></semantics></math>
for any integer <math alttext=3D"n" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" i=
d=3D"S4.SS3.p4.5.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>n</mi><annotation e=
ncoding=3D"application/x-tex">n</annotation></semantics></math>. One can ev=
en go on to define an <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" displa=
y=3D"inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.6.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi=
>N</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mro=
w><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semant=
ics></math>
self-adjoint Hamiltonian <math alttext=3D"H" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"=
inline" id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.7.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>H</mi><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">H</annotation></semantics></math> as=
 the infinitesimal generator of <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\l=
eft(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" =
id=3D"S4.SS3.p4.8.m8" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mrow>=
<mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn=
>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x=
-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></se=
mantics></math>,
so there is ultimately a Schr=C3=B6dinger equation underlying this system.<=
span class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote12"><sup class=3D"l=
tx_note_mark">12</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_not=
e_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">12</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_note">12</span>To define the unitary matrix <math alttext=3D"\Sigma^{t/=
\delta t}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m1" inten=
t=3D":literal"><semantics><msup><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><mrow=
><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=
=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><annotation encoding=3D"appl=
ication/x-tex">\Sigma^{t/\delta t}</annotation></semantics></math>, one
starts by using the fact that every permutation matrix is also unitary
to write the permutation matrix <math alttext=3D"\Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math"=
 display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi=
 mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-te=
x">\Sigma</annotation></semantics></math> as <math alttext=3D"V^{\dagger}DV=
" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m3" intent=3D":lit=
eral"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>V</mi><mo>=E2=80=A0</mo></msup><mo lspace=
=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>D</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=
=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application=
/x-tex">V^{\dagger}DV</annotation></semantics></math>
for some unitary matrix <math alttext=3D"V" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"i=
nline" id=3D"footnote12.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>V</mi><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">V</annotation></semantics></math> and =
some diagonal matrix <math alttext=3D"D" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inli=
ne" id=3D"footnote12.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>D</mi><annotati=
on encoding=3D"application/x-tex">D</annotation></semantics></math>, where
the entries of <math alttext=3D"D" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote12.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>D</mi><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">D</annotation></semantics></math> are the eigen=
values of <math alttext=3D"\Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote12.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi mathvariant=3D"normal=
">=CE=A3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Sigma</annotation>=
</semantics></math>.
Because <math alttext=3D"\Sigma" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote12.m8" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi mathvariant=3D"normal=
">=CE=A3</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Sigma</annotation>=
</semantics></math> is unitary, its eigenvalues are all
phase factors <math alttext=3D"\exp\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i\theta_{m}=
}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.=
m9" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>exp</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><=
mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><msub><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow></mrow><mo>=
)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\exp\mathopen{}\mat=
hclose{{\left(i\theta_{m}}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>, where <=
math alttext=3D"m=3D1,\dots,N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"=
footnote12.m10" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>=3D</mo>=
<mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi><mo>,</m=
o><mi>N</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">m=3D1,=
\dots,N</annotation></semantics></math>,
and where each phase <math alttext=3D"\theta_{m}" class=3D"ltx_Math" displa=
y=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m11" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi=
>=CE=B8</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\th=
eta_{m}</annotation></semantics></math> is a real number. Setting all the
eigenvalues to the power <math alttext=3D"t/\delta t" class=3D"ltx_Math" di=
splay=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m12" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow=
><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=
=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application=
/x-tex">t/\delta t</annotation></semantics></math>, so that they each take =
the
new form <math alttext=3D"\exp\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i\theta_{m}t/\de=
lta t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footno=
te12.m13" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>exp</mi><mrow><mi></mi><=
mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><msub><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mi>t</mi><m=
o>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation=
 encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\exp\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(i\theta_{m=
}t/\delta t}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>, one ends up with
the matrix <math alttext=3D"\Sigma^{t/\delta t}\equiv V^{\dagger}D^{t/\delt=
a t}V" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m14" intent=
=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A3</mi>=
<mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rs=
pace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=E2=89=A1</mo><mrow>=
<msup><mi>V</mi><mo>=E2=80=A0</mo></msup><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=
=E2=80=8B</mo><msup><mi>D</mi><mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</m=
i></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><=
/msup><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow></mr=
ow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Sigma^{t/\delta t}\equiv V^{=
\dagger}D^{t/\delta t}V</annotation></semantics></math>,
which is still unitary and now depends analytically on the time parameter
<math alttext=3D"t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.=
m15" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>t</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">t</annotation></semantics></math>. The quantum-theoretic Hami=
ltonian matrix <math alttext=3D"H" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=
=3D"footnote12.m16" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>H</mi><annotation en=
coding=3D"application/x-tex">H</annotation></semantics></math> for this sys=
tem
then has energy eigenvalues defined by <math alttext=3D"E_{m}\equiv-\hbar\t=
heta_{m}/\delta t" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.m=
17" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><=
mo>=E2=89=A1</mo><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=
=3D"normal">=E2=84=8F</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><=
msub><mi>=CE=B8</mi><mi>m</mi></msub></mrow><mo>/</mo><mi>=CE=B4</mi></mrow=
><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow></=
mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">E_{m}\equiv-\hbar\theta_{m}=
/\delta t</annotation></semantics></math>
for <math alttext=3D"m=3D1,\dots,N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" i=
d=3D"footnote12.m18" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>=3D=
</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=80=A6</mi><mo=
>,</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">m=
=3D1,\dots,N</annotation></semantics></math>, and is diagonalized by the sa=
me unitary matrix
<math alttext=3D"V" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote12.=
m19" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>V</mi><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">V</annotation></semantics></math> that diagonalizes <math alt=
