<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S5.SS5.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S5.SS5.p2.1">This classical wave function is the s=
tarting place for a representation
of classical deterministic physics known popularly as the =E2=80=98Koopman-=
von
Neumann=E2=80=99 formulation, due to its superficial resemblance
to work by Koopman (1931) and von Neumann
(1932a, 1932b)
in the 1930s. However, as pointed out explicitly by Jordan and Sudarshan
(1961), and in other work (Barandes
2026), Koopman and von Neumann were
actually using Hilbert spaces to represent <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_i=
talic" id=3D"S5.SS5.p2.1.1">observables</em>, rather
than to represent <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S5.SS5.p2.1.=
2">probability distributions</em>. The formulation
