etchy=3D"false">(</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcali=
graphic">=F0=9D=92=9E</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,</mo><mover accent=3D"true=
"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mo>~</mo></mover=
><mo>,</mo><msub><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraph=
ic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mover ac=
cent=3D"true"><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,=
</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>p</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,</mo><mover ac=
cent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi><mo>~=
</mo></mover><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"ap=
plication/x-tex">(\tilde{\mathcal{C}},\tilde{\mathcal{T}},\tilde{\mathcal{T=
}}_{0},\tilde{\Gamma},\tilde{p},\tilde{\mathcal{A}})</annotation></semantic=
s></math>
is a composite unistochastic process, and that the original indivisible
stochastic process <math alttext=3D"\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\mathcal{C=
},\mathcal{T},\mathcal{T}_{0},\Gamma,p,\mathcal{A}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_m=
ath_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS8.p1.3.m2" intent=3D":literal">=
<semantics><mrow><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathc=
aligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9E</mi><mo>,</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphi=
c">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=
=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=
=93</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic=
">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"a=
pplication/x-tex">\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{T},\mat=
hcal{T}_{0},\Gamma,p,\mathcal{A}}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
can be regarded as one of its subsystems. This conclusion completes
the proof of the stochastic-quantum theorem (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2309.03085v2#S4.E69" title=3D"In 4.1 Statement of the=
 Theorem =E2=80=A3 4 The Stochastic-Quantum Theorem =E2=80=A3 The Stochasti=
c-Quantum Theorem"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">69</span></a>).
QED</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report iss=
ue for preceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_subsection" id=3D"S5.SS9">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.9 </span>The Corresponding Qua=
ntum System</h3><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">R=
eport issue for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1.4">Corresponding to the dilated unistoch=
astic process <math alttext=3D"(\tilde{\mathcal{C}},\tilde{\mathcal{T}},\ti=
lde{\mathcal{T}}_{0},\tilde{\Gamma},\tilde{p},\tilde{\mathcal{A}})" class=
=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1.1.m1" intent=3D":literal">=
<semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi cl=
ass=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=9E</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,</=
mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=
=AF</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,</mo><msub><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=
=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraphic">=F0=9D=92=AF</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mn>0</mn>=
</msub><mo>,</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=93</=
mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>,</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>p</mi><mo>~</mo><=
/mover><mo>,</mo><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathcaligraph=
ic">=F0=9D=92=9C</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">(\tilde{\mathcal{C}},\tilde{\mat=
hcal{T}},\tilde{\mathcal{T}}_{0},\tilde{\Gamma},\tilde{p},\tilde{\mathcal{A=
}})</annotation></semantics></math>
is a quantum system based on a Hilbert space <math alttext=3D"\tilde{\mathc=
al{H}}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1.2.m2" intent=
=3D":literal"><semantics><mover accent=3D"true"><mi class=3D"ltx_font_mathc=
aligraphic">=E2=84=8B</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><annotation encoding=3D"applica=
tion/x-tex">\tilde{\mathcal{H}}</annotation></semantics></math>
of dimension <math alttext=3D"\tilde{N}\leq N^{3}" class=3D"ltx_Math" displ=
ay=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1.3.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><m=
over accent=3D"true"><mi>N</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mo>=E2=89=A4</mo><msup><m=
i>N</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">=
\tilde{N}\leq N^{3}</annotation></semantics></math>, with linear-unitary ti=
me evolution
encoded in the unitary time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"\tilde{U}\m=
athopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unpars=
ed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p1.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics=
><mrow><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>U</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mrow><mi></mi><m=
row><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mr=
ow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tild=
e{U}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></seman=
tics></math>.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">=
Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.5">Unistochastic matrices are not genera=
lly orthostochastic, meaning
that they are not guaranteed to be expressible in terms of real-orthogonal
matrices. As a consequence, if one is given an indivisible stochastic
process whose <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inl=
ine" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><=
mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semantics></ma=
th> transition matrix <math alttext=3D"\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t=
\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D=
"S5.SS9.p2.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=3D"no=
rmal">=CE=93</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"f=
alse">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation en=
coding=3D"application/x-tex">\Gamma\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow=
 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
is <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.5.1">already</em>=
 unistochastic, then there is no guarantee that the
corresponding <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inl=
ine" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.3.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><=
mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annot=
ation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semantics></ma=
th> unitary time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"U\mathopen{}\mathclose=
{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inli=
ne" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><m=
row><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo=
><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applicati=
on/x-tex">U\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation>=
</semantics></math>
can be assumed to be a real-orthogonal matrix. The stochastic-quantum
correspondence therefore implies that in order to provide Hilbert-space
representations for the most general kinds of indivisible stochastic
processes, the complex numbers <math alttext=3D"\mathbb{C}" class=3D"ltx_Ma=
th" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p2.5.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics=
><mi>=E2=84=82</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathbb{C}</a=
nnotation></semantics></math> will be an important
feature of quantum theory.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"dis=
play: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3.4">Whether in that case or more generall=
y, of course, one is always free
to start with an <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"=
inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</m=
i><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><an=
notation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semantics><=
/math> time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"\Theta\mathopen{}\mathclose=
{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"inli=
ne" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvari=
ant=3D"normal">=CE=98</mi><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stre=
tchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><anno=
tation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\Theta\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t\=
leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
in (<a class=3D"ltx_ref" href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2309.03085v2#S5.E72=
" title=3D"In 5.1 The Time-Evolution Operator =E2=80=A3 5 Proof of the Theo=
rem =E2=80=A3 The Stochastic-Quantum Theorem"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_r=
ef_tag">72</span></a>) whose individual
entries are all real. With that choice, the <math alttext=3D"\tilde{N}\time=
s\tilde{N}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3.3.m3" int=
ent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>N</mi><mo>~</m=
o></mover><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mover accen=
t=3D"true"><mi>N</mi><mo>~</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">\tilde{N}\times\tilde{N}</annotation></semantics></math>
unitary time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"\tilde{U}\mathopen{}\mathc=
lose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"=
inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p3.4.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mover a=
ccent=3D"true"><mi>U</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><=
mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)=
</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{U}\mathopen{}=
\mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>
obtained from the Stinespring dilation theorem will likewise be real,
and will therefore be an orthogonal matrix.</p><button class=3D"sr-only but=
ton" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S5.SS9.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S5.SS9.p4.2">However, it is important to keep in m=
ind that from the point of view
of the stochastic-quantum correspondence, the Hilbert-space representations
of a given indivisible stochastic process are convenient fictions,
and so one is entirely free to assume that they involve the complex
numbers anyway. Assuming that a given choice of Hilbert-space representatio=
n
is defined over the complex numbers, rather than merely over the real
numbers, allows one to take advantage of the spectral theorem, eigenvectors
of the time-evolution operator <math alttext=3D"\tilde{U}\mathopen{}\mathcl=
ose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"i=
nline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p4.1.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mover ac=
cent=3D"true"><mi>U</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mrow><mi></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><m=
i>t</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mo>)<=
/mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{U}\mathopen{}\=
mathclose{{\left(t\leftarrow 0}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>,
and anti-unitary operators. Assuming appropriate smoothness conditions
in time, one can further make use of a self-adjoint Hamiltonian <math altte=
xt=3D"\tilde{H}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_u=
nparsed" display=3D"inline" id=3D"S5.SS9.p4.2.m2" intent=3D":literal"><sema=
ntics><mrow><mover accent=3D"true"><mi>H</mi><mo>~</mo></mover><mrow><mi></=
mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">\tilde{H}\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(t}}\right=
)</annotation></semantics></math>
with real-valued energy eigenvalues, as well as the Schr=C3=B6dinger equati=
on.
To the extent that these mathematical constructs are often taken by
textbooks to be indisputable features of quantum systems, the complex
numbers become an unavoidable part of quantum theory.<span class=3D"ltx_not=
e ltx_role_footnote" id=3D"footnote14"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">14</sup=
><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=
=3D"ltx_note_mark">14</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">14</span>Ev=
en if one assumes that a given choice of Hilbert-space representation
is defined over the complex numbers, one can always double the dimension
of the Hilbert space from <math alttext=3D"N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D=
"inline" id=3D"footnote14.m1" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>N</mi><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N</annotation></semantics></math> to=
 <math alttext=3D"2N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote1=
4.m2" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo lspace=3D"0em" rsp=
ace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applicat=
ion/x-tex">2N</annotation></semantics></math> and represent the imaginary
unit <math alttext=3D"i\equiv\sqrt{-1}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inlin=
e" id=3D"footnote14.m3" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=
=E2=89=A1</mo><msqrt><mrow><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msqrt></mro=
w><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">i\equiv\sqrt{-1}</annotation><=
/semantics></math> by the <math alttext=3D"2\times 2" class=3D"ltx_Math" di=
splay=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote14.m4" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow>=
<mn>2</mn><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mn>2</mn></=
mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">2\times 2</annotation></sem=
antics></math> real matrix <math alttext=3D"\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\b=
egin{smallmatrix}0&amp;-1\\
1&amp;0\end{smallmatrix}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"i=
nline" id=3D"footnote14.m5" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>=
</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mtable columnspacing=3D"5pt" rowspacing=3D"0pt"><mtr>=
<mtd><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">0</mn></mtd><mtd><mrow><mo mathsize=3D"0.700e=
m">=E2=88=92</mo><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mt=
d><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">0</mn>=
</mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=3D=
"application/x-tex">\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\begin{smallmatrix}0&amp;-=
1\\
1&amp;0\end{smallmatrix}}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>, in which=
 case all <math alttext=3D"N\times N" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline"=
 id=3D"footnote14.m6" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo ls=
pace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation=
 encoding=3D"application/x-tex">N\times N</annotation></semantics></math> u=
nitary matrices become <math alttext=3D"2N\times 2N" class=3D"ltx_Math" dis=
play=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote14.m7" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><=
mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>N<=
/mi></mrow><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mn>2</mn><=
/mrow><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>N</mi></mrow><ann=
otation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">2N\times 2N</annotation></semantics>=
</math>
real orthogonal matrices (Myrheim 1999).
Interestingly, one can then also represent the complex-conjugation
operation <math alttext=3D"K" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"f=
ootnote14.m8" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>K</mi><annotation encoding=
=3D"application/x-tex">K</annotation></semantics></math> needed for anti-un=
itary operators as a <math alttext=3D"2\times 2" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=
=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote14.m9" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mn>2=
</mn><mo lspace=3D"0.222em" rspace=3D"0.222em">=C3=97</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow>=
<annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">2\times 2</annotation></semantic=
s></math>
real matrix <math alttext=3D"\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\begin{smallmatri=
x}0&amp;1\\
1&amp;0\end{smallmatrix}}}\right)" class=3D"ltx_math_unparsed" display=3D"i=
nline" id=3D"footnote14.m10" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi=
></mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mtable columnspacing=3D"5pt" rowspacing=3D"0pt"><mtr=
><mtd><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">0</mn></mtd><mtd><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">1<=
/mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn mathsize=3D"0.700em">1</mn></mtd><mtd><mn mat=
hsize=3D"0.700em">0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\mathopen{}\mathclose{{\left(\b=
egin{smallmatrix}0&amp;1\\
1&amp;0\end{smallmatrix}}}\right)</annotation></semantics></math>, which ha=
ppens to coincide with the first Pauli sigma matrix <math alttext=3D"\sigma=
_{x}" class=3D"ltx_Math" display=3D"inline" id=3D"footnote14.m11" intent=3D=
":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>=CF=83</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><annotation enc=
oding=3D"application/x-tex">\sigma_{x}</annotation></semantics></math>
(Stueckelberg 1960). However, this
approach still ultimately preserves the algebraic structure of the
complex numbers in the Hilbert space, in the sense that they will
correspond to a subalgebra of matrices on the overall Hilbert space
that commute with the Hamiltonian and all the system=E2=80=99s observables.
Hence, this approach does not truly eliminate the complex numbers
from the Hilbert-space formalism of quantum theory. Moreover, using
this =E2=80=98real=E2=80=99 representation means that
the Hilbert spaces of composite systems will not factorize as neatly
into Hilbert spaces for their constituent subsystems.</span></span></span><=
/p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue f=
or preceding element</button>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section class=3D"ltx_section" id=3D"S6">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">6 </span>Discussion and Future Work=
</h2><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue=
 for preceding element</button>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S6.p1">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S6.p1.1">The unitarily evolving quantum system tha=
t lies on the other side
of the stochastic-quantum correspondence is not limited to a <em class=3D"l=
tx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S6.p1.1.1">commutative</em>
algebra of observables represented by operators that are diagonal
in the configuration basis.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"di=
splay: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S6.p2">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S6.p2.1">Indeed, as explained in other work (Baran=
des 2025),
one can model the quantum measurement process of an observable represented
by an <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic" id=3D"S6.p2.1.1">arbitrary</em=
> self-adjoint operator in terms of a unistochastic
process that contains a subject system, a measuring device, and an
environment, all as explicitly defined subsystems. By taking the measuring
device=E2=80=99s allowed configurations to correspond to definite readings
of outcomes, and by taking the transition matrix for the overall unistochas=
tic
process to be based on precisely the type of unitary time-evolution
operator employed in standard textbook treatments of the measurement
process, one inevitably finds that the measuring device ends up in
one of its measurement-reading configurations with a stochastic probability
given by the general form of the Born rule. Hence, in principle, one
has access to a quantum system=E2=80=99s entire <em class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_f=
ont_italic" id=3D"S6.p2.1.2">noncommutative</em> algebra
of observables.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;=
">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S6.p3">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S6.p3.1">In essence, the stochastic-quantum corres=
pondence therefore suggests
that every quantum system may ultimately be an indivisible stochastic
process in disguise. From this standpoint, the usual Hilbert-space
formulation is then just a convenient mathematical layer on top of
a system evolving stochastically along some trajectory through a configurat=
ion
space in a highly non-Markovian way.</p><button class=3D"sr-only button" st=
yle=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</button>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S6.p4">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S6.p4.1">With the stochastic-quantum correspondenc=
e in hand, one can refer
other exotic features of quantum systems back to their associated
indivisible stochastic processes to give those features a more physically
transparent interpretation. For example, interference and entanglement
can be understood as artifacts of the generic indivisibility of the
stochastic dynamics. Moreover, from the perspective of this stochastic-quan=
tum
correspondence, what gives quantum computers their possible advantage
over classical computers is their access to dynamical laws that are
indivisible, and therefore extremely non-Markovian.</p><button class=3D"sr-=
only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding element</b=
utton>
</div>
<div class=3D"ltx_para" id=3D"S6.p5">
<p class=3D"ltx_p" id=3D"S6.p5.1">This overall approach to quantum foundati=
ons therefore sheds new light
on some of the strangest features of quantum theory, in addition to
suggesting novel applications of quantum computers. This approach
might even provide a helpful stepping stone for the development of
self-consistent generalizations of quantum theory itself.</p><button class=
=3D"sr-only button" style=3D"display: none;">Report issue for preceding ele=
ment</button>
</div>
</section>
